Title: Linking forum posts - warhol-02-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Were there copyright issues regarding Andy Warhol?
Input.posts:
It occurred to me that Warhol walked a thin line by appropriating commercial art labels and iconic images in his work. Campbell's soup is apparently ok with it now, since they sold tomato soup in Warhol 'signed' cans recently. What about then?
Upvotes:
0
Don't know about soup, but Warhol silkscreened 'Flowers' from a photograph lifted from a magazine. He didn't ask the photographer for permission. She sued. He lost.
Upvotes:
1

Input.threadtitle: Today's New York Times Art Section Full of Warhol
Input.posts:
I was pleased today to open my copy of the New York Times and find a full page picture of Andy Warhol wearing a sandwich board of Race Riot at the Factory, 1964. The page is an ad from Christies. There is a Warhol quote: 'During the '60's, I think people forgot what emotions were supposed to be. And I don't think they've ever remembered.' The caption reads: 'The year was 1964. Photographs in newspapers across the United States revealed a terrible truth--the land of the free was a battlefield scarred by deeply rooted racial inequality. Amid these headlines, Andy Warhol produced a series of works depicting an attack on civil rights protesters in Birmingham, Alabama. Fifty years later, these groundbreaking works exemplify Warhol;s ability to create art that defined an era.' Another full page shows Warhol's Race Riot (1964) and invites readers to view it for an auction on Post-War and Contemporary Art on May 13. Another announcement from Blain di Donna Gallery announces Warhol:Jackie through May 17. Right under that is an announcement of an Acquavella Gallery showing of Jean Michel Basquiat Drawing : Work from the Schorr Family Foundation. I share this info just to underline that the materials we are engagng in this course are extremely timely in the broader art scene. Of course, that will not come as a surprise to most fellow students. We already seem to be Warholians to one extent or another. But it is so interesting to see that Warhol is very present still today. And if you have the luck to live in or near Manhattan, why don't you go to these events and share your impressions with the rest of us who live far from the Big Apple?
Upvotes:
2
I wish I were near Manhattan so I could attend a couple of these events!

0

Input.threadtitle: Marilyn Diptych 1962
Input.posts:
This work was done in the weeks after Marilyn Monroe's death in 1962. One of Warhol's themes was death and I think the right hand side shows that - as Marilyn fades away The work is certainly iconic and has been much-copied (Madonna springs to mind) and much-parodied (The Simpsons)
Upvotes:
5
I intend to visit the Tate soon to view this art.
Upvotes:
0
I do not agree that the ubiquitous repetition of Marilyn Monroe's face signifies death. Since each repetition is different but subtle I feel that there is a quality of alivness to the pictures.. John Breeskin
Upvotes:
1
I think the coloured part means Life, celebrity, beauty ; the other half in black and white stands for Death, something that fades away ( life, beauty ... Who knows?).

Input.threadtitle: Marilyn Diptych 1962
Input.posts:
This work was done in the weeks after Marilyn Monroe's death in 1962. One of Warhol's themes was death and I think the right hand side shows that - as Marilyn fades away The work is certainly iconic and has been much-copied (Madonna springs to mind) and much-parodied (The Simpsons)
Upvotes:

I intend to visit the Tate soon to view this art.

I do not agree that the ubiquitous repetition of Marilyn Monroe's face signifies death. Since each repetition is different but subtle I feel that there is a quality of alivness to the pictures.. John Breeskin

Input.threadtitle: The Rolling Stones Andy Warhol Zippers and Sticky Fingers
Input.posts:
The 1970s witnessed a flood of open sexuality - post-Stonewall riot, birth of disco, Transcendental Meditation and Swinger's clubs are all coming signs of the sexual revolution. Sex, or rather, the more open attitude about it was everywhere. Warhol, a quiet, conservative Catholic homosexual must have had a sigh of relief - after having fully recovered from an assassination attempt (by Valerie Solanas) he surrounded himself with me and began to feverishly create works that walks the line between art and pornography. When asked to create the cover and concept for the Rolling Stones' 'Sticky Fingers' album Warhol was quick to capitalize on the sexual allure of lead singer Mick Jagger (The image is NOT of Jagger by the way) and Warhol's casual remark to Jagger that it would be interesting to have an album cover with a zipper on it. When you undid the belt buckle, white cotton underwear stamped with Andy Warhol was revealed (it also served to protect the vinyl from the real metal zipper). Gone is the playful innuendo of a large banana (from the Velvet Underground) finding in this work, Warhol flaunting his voyeuristic sexuality (a male with a rather large penis), his interest in combing art with mass consumption (the album would be one of the Rolling Stones' most successful), along with the continuation of his fascination with provoking the boring. Please upflag this post if you've read it or bought the album!
Upvotes:
15
This was such great album cover! I remember seeing it on display in a record store at the time, and would've have bought it if I'd had enough money. Unfortunately, the zippers caused serious problems in the distribution process, such as tearing the cellophane wrappers and catching on each other in stacks. Andy must have conceived this as an artwork on the wall, and not packed into cartons sitting on forklifts.
Upvotes:
1
Alice Thanks for reading and replying to my post (maybe give it an up flag?) I worked for years at a record store and saw hundreds of this album fly out the door. It was too bad that later reissues did away with the real zipper and cloth undies ...
Upvotes:
0
Warhol did a quite few album covers including Love you live.According to: http://kingydesignhistory2012.wordpress.com/2012/05/01/kay-post-6-musicgraphics/ RCA Records hired Warhol, along with another freelance artist, Sid Maurer, to design album covers and promotional materials. I wonder who Mick is biting and why. The hand looks feminine. However, given their relationship, it might be Keith. Yes, I know, there is no skull ring or have I the wrong hand. The count Basie is a little tamer and nothing risque about Hugo Winterhalter album. Both I think would be early work.
Upvotes:
3
Darryl: Thanks for commenting on my thread and it shows how quick corporate America is quick to capitaliz on the usccessful. The Gershwin cover comes from a drawing Warhol did in the 50s - probably reflecting the age of the music. If I saw the Basie out of context, I might even be hard pressed to vote it a Warhol cover. As for the Stone - no doubt - and maybe the hand is the hand that feed you. :-)
Upvotes:
0
Awesome post man, I didn't know about the Sticky Fingers cover, but I find it very controversial even by today standards, a bold move for Warhol and the Rolling Stones.

Input.threadtitle: Porn as art ?
Input.posts:
It seems to me that Warhol is treating pornography in the same way, essentially, as he treated Campbell's Soup, in that he's taken something that already existed commercially ( even if 'underground') and made it into art by putting the Warhol stamp on it. 'Blow Job' is, I think, interesting as it's not unlike the product of the underground porn studios of the time who tended to offer more than they delivered in terms of content. The same is true of 'Hollywood'. I remember the posters for the film 'Barbarella' prominently stating that 'She strips in space' ( I've no idea if she did or not, I've never seen it but I'm confident that it wouldn't have been the 'full monty'.).
Upvotes:
4
Barbarella never stripped (in film ) . Guess Warhol took what was a common way of thinking and turned it upside down . His movies are hard to find i guess .
Upvotes:
1
Oh yes she did! She was played by Jane Fonda. It was in the opening sequence of the movie. You must have seen a censored version.
Upvotes:
0
Perhaps, as a devout Catholic he was challenging his own religious beliefs. http://www.patheos.com/blogs/godandthemachine/2012/10/warhol/
Upvotes:
0
Pornography is defined as writing or images designed to stimulate sexual excitement. It's constantly around us as entertainment. I'm watching Game of Thrones and that's a lot more graphic any any couch Andy had. The slippery slope of course is when there is lack of consent, or harm is being done.
Upvotes:
5
I've been thinking about this ( probably not good for me !) and it seems to me that , historically, there was no shortage of 'pornography' in art, including plenty of homo-erotic depictions , from Ancient Greek and Roman vases and paintings through prints from Japan and China and 'secret works' by Rowlandson etc and Aubrey Beardsley etc. So what was different here ? Is it the media that Warhol was using, is a 'pornographic' photo somehow more 'pornographic' than a lithograph ?

Input.threadtitle: Vulgarity or aestheticism ??
Input.posts:
How one can differentiate nudity from vulgarity to aestheticism ? One can view the same thing in very aesthetics way and to another's opinion it can be vulgar? So what's the perspective behind it ?
Upvotes:
0
I'm not sure... Perhaps it is all about presentation and atmosphere? For example, when framed black and white portraits of nudes (male or female) are displayed in a gallery, is it more aesthetically pleasing than seeing colour photographs in a crumpled magazine you found under a bed?
Upvotes:
0
I think as others have said, it can be very much in the eye of the beholder. I do believe that the human body is a beautiful thing, so a black and white photograph can very much be aesthetically pleasing. I would find it more so than a magazine, but then we also associate different things with a magazine than we do photos in a gallery. The magazine has certain thoughts and feelings that it pulls out. We look at it as 'a bit naughty,' and for a different type of 'personal pleasure.' The photograph is a different sort of pleasure. Look, don't touch, take in the beauty, but not in a sexually stimulating way, because of the location and surroundings.
Upvotes:
3
I agree that the context in which you're viewing an image infers its intention. If you're told something is 'art', you might be more open to it and judge it less harshly than if you were flipping through a magazine in your dentist's office and came across a picture that could be classified as 'vulgar'. We might assume that the people who put that image in the magazine had the intention of selling their product through sex, or that the artist is trying to show beauty in the human body. There are always people who will find some 'art' vulgar, and find 'vulgar' images artistic. It really is about the viewer and their experiences with art and life.
Upvotes:
2
But if that is the case, then the discourse here is about context and less about subject matter. Given that, why is the speaker's shadow so starkly outlined against the banana in the introductory video? Given the context of the film ( a class discuss on Warhol's sexuality), how intentional was the mise-en-scene of that image? The context of the image brings to the viewer a heightened awareness of the shot composition and doubles back on itself by causing the viewer to becoming doubly aware of the sexuality of both the spoken content and the image.
Upvotes:
2
Well, the banana is phallic, so makes a good juxtaposition within the context of the lecture. I think you're right. The theme focuses on the content as a tease. That it is the idea that something will be seen or presented that is openly sexual, but then it isn't. Warhol is making you use your mind to see the 'sex' in something. When viewed on it's own, do you think sex or do you think banana? It is interesting. Normally I think banana, not penis/sex. Have you ever seen this copy of the album cover? Do you think it would be seen as a penis, or a banana?

4
The color definitely is what makes it more prominently phallic. If it weren't a red banana, I would think, it's a banana.

Title: Linking forum posts - warhol-02-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: 'Blow Job' in its time and place
Input.posts:
It's worth taking a look at 'Blow Job'. http://vimeo.com/45258317 Like many Warhol films, it's both boring and fascinating. In the context of the times (I was there), it wash't a tease, it was downright shocking. In a more sexually conventional vein, Russ Meyer was making commercially successful heterosexual movies that didn't show the actual sex (cut away to undulating curtains). Warhol, always wanting to shock, created his homoerotic soft porn. It's a 'tease' only if you think that showing the 'full Monty' is expected. It wasn't expected in that time and place. But by using that title, showing the face of the pretty young man, and then ending with a post-coital cigarette -- that was really pushing the line. Which is what Warhol was doing in all of his art at the time.
Upvotes:
6
I agree that the film is both boring and interesting. From the title the viewer attempts to interpret every move of the actor. The initial process of unzipping and preparing, if you will, for the performance maybe going down below the camera, is obvious; but then the film quickly becomes undulating, slow, very little facial grimacing and contorting. Here I sense the difference between this film and stark pornography of the period with quick gyrating bodies and mouths screaming in sensual arousal, almost violent in its action. I think the erotic element is first in the movement of the young man's head from center screen off to the left and back, moving back and forth reminding one of the actions of the theoretical invisible performer down below. Then the darkening of the facial structure leaving only the nose lit seems obvious yet obfuscating. Interestingly one can't read well the moment of supposed or real climax. I guess we could all choose a moment and be close, but never sure. This is theater or film after all. I love the smoking of the cigarette which reminds me of every celluloid love story from the period where cigarettes appear, usually both in the man's mouth to be lit and giving one to his lover: vamp or consort. The least our protagonist could have done was light two and send one down to his silent unseen partner! The ending repeats the beginning as the young man tidies up, stuffing every thing back away from everyone's view. I find Blow Job to be much in line with his machine-like desire to limit movement, stop time if you will, maybe thereby pushing the inevitable further and further away.
Upvotes:
3
In the context of the time, being gay and being comfortable with being gay had to be like knowing an inside joke. Professor Davis mentioned that Warhol was generally perceived as being asexual. I remember also hearing (from him or someone else, I don't recall) that he was strictly a voyeur. Those of us in the hinterlands couldn't handle our role models as gay, at that point. It seems to me that this inside joke may have led to other inside jokes, such as the hidden and the tease in his films.
Upvotes:
1
I'm thinking that the voyeur aspect is important here and in many of his other erotic films. Voyeurs can be satisfied with both the boring parts and the partial views. The joy is in the watching -- you watch a man sleep for six hours or stare at all the faces that come with a (get this) 30 minute fellatio. In real porn, there's a lot of acting going on so that the passion seems endless and fabulous. Voyeurs know it doesn't really work that way. They love watching real life stuff, boring conversations, people picking at pimples, because they get to see life as it actually happens. Even Warhol's 'Screen Tests' are, in their own way, voyeurism. On the gay thing, I agree that there are a lot of inside jokes. But also some not so funny screams for recognition. Stonewall and breaking out into the streets were still to come. Gay was very secret, very dangerous in 1964. Warhol -- like Jean Genet -- was slinging it out there through his art, trying to bring to the surface what was hidden way below.
Upvotes:
7
You have come up with a very interesting idea here, regarding the use of voyeurism. I really did not see this as being a part of his art until watching the 'Blowjob' film. Then to read you comment, I had a real 'aha!' moment there. This is why I love the discussion forums!
Upvotes:
1
Some of the perceived sex is really vulgar, and I just have to wonder if AW had some personal problems with this issue ?? Using the art to cover up inadequecies ???
Upvotes:
0
Thanks, James, for giving the URL to watch the movie. First time I watch it and I liked this movie. Actually there are man interesting elements: the colours, the absence of sounds, and all not shown, which invite you to imagine. Everything moves the viewer to create the own images. This is what happens in many pieces of art: the artist shows us just a part and we have to discover the rest.
Upvotes:
1
While life was dangerous in the gay world of New York, still there were more possibilities in the mid to late sixties to produce and play which few other places allowed. Boys in the Band 'came out' in 1968, Charles Ludlam's Ridiculous Theater Company began in 1967. Interestingly Ronald Tavel wrote two plays originally intended as scripts for Warhol, 'Shower' and 'The life of Juanita Castro' . Edi Sedgwick was to star in Shower but she refused. These were premiered at the Coda Gallery in the city in 1965-- and began The theater of the Ridiculous. I came across a group headed by the architect Horace Gifford, entitled the Fire Island Modernists, who erected buildings on the islands from 1961 - 1981, It still astounds me that Jean Genet wrote 'Our Lady of the Flowers' in 1943 and Blacks in 1958 which led the Black Panthers to embrace him when he was finally allowed into the United States in 1970. While I agree that Warhol helped the non mainstream and alternative cultures to gain some footing, I still can't place him as a signicicant influence on all of urban society. He is, though, an intriguing and innovative artists. Reviewing 'Blow Job', just one more comment, I didn't see any credits, but that could just be the copy I viewed. With this is mind, is it not just an assumption that the pleasurer in the film is in fact a male? Just a thought.
Upvotes:
2
I think the most amusing aspect of this film is the question of who, if anyone, was performing the sexual act. What if young master Bookwalter was putting it all on? Is it still vulgar pornography if it is all in the viewer's imagination?
Upvotes:
1
James thank you for the post. Interesting post, The film is AW way to be provocative and cutting edge at the same time. I never meet Aw but I was aquainted in NYC with people that knew him well. He most likely have some inadequacies as Michael pointed above, and he was fascinated not only with famous but also with beautiful people. I also heard he was a vouyeurs however I never heard of any one saying that they had have sex with Andy, and I knew people that assisted to some of the drag party organized at Halston house or in his house in Mauntock. NY., even though they have a high profile those parties where private, by invitation only, in this social circle people talk and information goes arround, and gossip spread fast. It is not doubt about his sexual preferences, However I think he was sexually repressed, He lived it through his art

0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Thanks, Joseph, for providing all of this very useful contextualisation. You're right - New York in the 1960s was a place which allowed for some quite risqué experimentation and art production. There's also an argument to be made that there was more malleability and flexibility in terms of identity politics and roles before the gay rights movement… None of Warhol's films have credits sequences: they just start and stop. (When he moved to producing films in 1968, with Paul Morrissey directing, credits started to appear.) Your question is a really good one: how do we know the gender of the person out of frame? As Marion suggests below, maybe there's actually nobody there at all!

Input.threadtitle: 'Blow Job' in its time and place
Input.posts:
It's worth taking a look at 'Blow Job'. http://vimeo.com/45258317 Like many Warhol films, it's both boring and fascinating. In the context of the times (I was there), it wash't a tease, it was downright shocking. In a more sexually conventional vein, Russ Meyer was making commercially successful heterosexual movies that didn't show the actual sex (cut away to undulating curtains). Warhol, always wanting to shock, created his homoerotic soft porn. It's a 'tease' only if you think that showing the 'full Monty' is expected. It wasn't expected in that time and place. But by using that title, showing the face of the pretty young man, and then ending with a post-coital cigarette -- that was really pushing the line. Which is what Warhol was doing in all of his art at the time.
Upvotes:
6
I agree that the film is both boring and interesting. From the title the viewer attempts to interpret every move of the actor. The initial process of unzipping and preparing, if you will, for the performance maybe going down below the camera, is obvious; but then the film quickly becomes undulating, slow, very little facial grimacing and contorting. Here I sense the difference between this film and stark pornography of the period with quick gyrating bodies and mouths screaming in sensual arousal, almost violent in its action. I think the erotic element is first in the movement of the young man's head from center screen off to the left and back, moving back and forth reminding one of the actions of the theoretical invisible performer down below. Then the darkening of the facial structure leaving only the nose lit seems obvious yet obfuscating. Interestingly one can't read well the moment of supposed or real climax. I guess we could all choose a moment and be close, but never sure. This is theater or film after all. I love the smoking of the cigarette which reminds me of every celluloid love story from the period where cigarettes appear, usually both in the man's mouth to be lit and giving one to his lover: vamp or consort. The least our protagonist could have done was light two and send one down to his silent unseen partner! The ending repeats the beginning as the young man tidies up, stuffing every thing back away from everyone's view. I find Blow Job to be much in line with his machine-like desire to limit movement, stop time if you will, maybe thereby pushing the inevitable further and further away.

In the context of the time, being gay and being comfortable with being gay had to be like knowing an inside joke. Professor Davis mentioned that Warhol was generally perceived as being asexual. I remember also hearing (from him or someone else, I don't recall) that he was strictly a voyeur. Those of us in the hinterlands couldn't handle our role models as gay, at that point. It seems to me that this inside joke may have led to other inside jokes, such as the hidden and the tease in his films.

I'm thinking that the voyeur aspect is important here and in many of his other erotic films. Voyeurs can be satisfied with both the boring parts and the partial views. The joy is in the watching -- you watch a man sleep for six hours or stare at all the faces that come with a (get this) 30 minute fellatio. In real porn, there's a lot of acting going on so that the passion seems endless and fabulous. Voyeurs know it doesn't really work that way. They love watching real life stuff, boring conversations, people picking at pimples, because they get to see life as it actually happens. Even Warhol's 'Screen Tests' are, in their own way, voyeurism. On the gay thing, I agree that there are a lot of inside jokes. But also some not so funny screams for recognition. Stonewall and breaking out into the streets were still to come. Gay was very secret, very dangerous in 1964. Warhol -- like Jean Genet -- was slinging it out there through his art, trying to bring to the surface what was hidden way below.

While life was dangerous in the gay world of New York, still there were more possibilities in the mid to late sixties to produce and play which few other places allowed. Boys in the Band 'came out' in 1968, Charles Ludlam's Ridiculous Theater Company began in 1967. Interestingly Ronald Tavel wrote two plays originally intended as scripts for Warhol, 'Shower' and 'The life of Juanita Castro' . Edi Sedgwick was to star in Shower but she refused. These were premiered at the Coda Gallery in the city in 1965-- and began The theater of the Ridiculous. I came across a group headed by the architect Horace Gifford, entitled the Fire Island Modernists, who erected buildings on the islands from 1961 - 1981, It still astounds me that Jean Genet wrote 'Our Lady of the Flowers' in 1943 and Blacks in 1958 which led the Black Panthers to embrace him when he was finally allowed into the United States in 1970. While I agree that Warhol helped the non mainstream and alternative cultures to gain some footing, I still can't place him as a signicicant influence on all of urban society. He is, though, an intriguing and innovative artists. Reviewing 'Blow Job', just one more comment, I didn't see any credits, but that could just be the copy I viewed. With this is mind, is it not just an assumption that the pleasurer in the film is in fact a male? Just a thought.
